The Theory of Evolution is a scientific explanation for how species change over time and evolve from one form to another. It was first proposed by Charles Darwin in 1859 through his book "On the Origin of Species." 

The process starts with natural selection. This means that only those organisms best suited for their environment will survive and reproduce. Over many generations, these favorable traits become more common among offspring as they continue passing them down. 

For example, if there's a lot of food available near water sources, then fish who can swim fast may have better chances at survival than slower ones. Faster swimmers would be able to find food more easily and thus pass on their speedy genes to future generations. In this way, faster swimming becomes increasingly prevalent within the population over time.

Another key concept here is genetic mutation - small changes or variations in DNA (deoxyribonucleic acid) sequences between individuals. Mutations occur randomly but play a crucial role in driving evolution because some might confer advantages while others don't. These advantageous mutations help create new characteristics which contribute towards adaptation and diversification of life forms throughout history.

In summary, according to the Theory of Evolution:
- Life evolved from simpler single celled organisms;
- Genetic variation exists due to random mutations;
- Phenotypic diversity arises when different combinations of alleles exist within populations;
- Natural Selection favors those individuals whose traits give them higher reproductive success under specific environmental conditions;
- Adaptation occurs via inheritance of beneficial traits leading to speciation (the formation of distinct groups);
- Extinction happens naturally due to geological events like ice ages or volcanic eruptions, competition amongst species resulting from limited resources etc.;
- Humans emerged after millions years ago during Pleistocene epoch following our ancestral lineage back to 6 million years ago.

